The answer is \textbf{false}

We try each combination for \emph{a}

\begin{align*}
4(0) &\equiv 0 \mod{10} \\
4(1) &\equiv 4 \mod{10} \\
4(2) &\equiv 8 \mod{10} \\
4(3) &\equiv 2 \mod{10} \\
4(4) &\equiv 6 \mod{10} \\
4(5) &\equiv 0 \mod{10} \\
4(6) &\equiv 4 \mod{10} \\
4(7) &\equiv 8 \mod{10} \\
4(8) &\equiv 2 \mod{10} \\
4(9) &\equiv 6 \mod{10}
\end{align*}

As we can see, we have two solutions given by
$\displaystyle a \equiv 4,9 \mod{10}$ and so the statement is false.
